# Structurer (Sales and Trading)

## Overview
Structurers design customized financial products and derivatives solutions for institutional clients, combining technical expertise in pricing with commercial acumen to meet specific investment objectives or risk management needs.

## Core Responsibilities
- Design bespoke structured products including derivatives, structured notes, and complex financing arrangements tailored to specific client investment objectives and risk parameters
- Lead pricing processes using advanced quantitative models, running scenario analyses, and coordinating execution with trading desks to ensure competitive and accurate product terms
- Present complex structure proposals to clients, explaining technical payoffs clearly while negotiating terms, pricing, and documentation to win competitive mandates
- Coordinate cross-functionally with sales, trading, legal, compliance, operations, and risk teams to manage full transaction lifecycle from initial pitch to settlement
- Conduct competitive analysis and market intelligence, monitoring competitor offerings, regulatory developments, and innovations to maintain market-leading product capabilities
- Assess comprehensive risks in proposed structures including market, credit, operational, and regulatory risks while ensuring compliance with ASIC requirements and disclosure obligations

## Key Skills Required

### Technical & Quantitative
- Advanced derivatives pricing across asset classes including exotic options, path-dependent payoffs, and correlation products
- Quantitative modeling proficiency in Python/MATLAB for Monte Carlo simulation, finite difference methods, and pricing analysis
- Deep understanding of volatility modeling including smile, surface, local vol, and stochastic volatility frameworks
- Bloomberg Terminal expertise for derivatives pricing, market data analysis, and structuring tools (SWPM, DLIB, OVME)

### Commercial & Interpersonal
- Exceptional client communication skills translating complex technical concepts into clear business language for C-suite audiences
- Persuasive presentation and negotiation abilities to pitch structures competitively and close complex deals
- Creative problem-solving for designing novel solutions addressing specific client hedging or investment challenges
- Strong project management coordinating multiple simultaneous deals with tight deadlines across diverse stakeholders

### Regulatory & Documentation
- Expert knowledge of ASIC derivatives regulation including product intervention powers and Design & Distribution Obligations
- Understanding of ISDA documentation, hedge accounting standards (IFRS 9), and Basel III capital implications
- Expertise in product disclosure requirements differentiating retail versus wholesale structured product obligations

## Work Mode

### Client Engagement & Business Development (30-35%)
Client meetings presenting structure proposals, explaining complex payoffs, responding to RFPs, negotiating terms and pricing. Building senior relationships with corporate treasurers, CFOs, and institutional investors to position bespoke solutions.

### Analysis & Structuring (35-40%)
Designing customized solutions, building sophisticated pricing models in Excel/Python, running Monte Carlo simulations, developing term sheets, analyzing risk-return trade-offs, creating scenario analyses, and innovating new product types for market opportunities.

### Cross-Functional Coordination (20-25%)
Working with traders on hedging strategies, coordinating with legal teams on ISDA documentation, managing compliance approval processes, liaising with risk on capital implications, overseeing execution and settlement, providing post-trade client support.

### Market Intelligence & Strategy (10-15%)
Researching competitor product offerings, monitoring regulatory developments from ASIC and global bodies, staying current on derivatives markets and volatility trends, contributing to thought leadership through publications and conference presentations.

### Team Leadership & Mentorship (Variable)
Senior roles involve managing structuring teams, mentoring junior structurers, conducting quality control on pricing models and term sheets, setting product strategy, and building cross-functional partnerships with sales and trading leadership.

## Workplace Culture
Fast-paced, intellectually rigorous environment requiring technical excellence combined with commercial judgment. Collaborative cross-functional teamwork with traders, sales, quants, legal, and compliance while maintaining client focus.

## Career Path
- Entry: Junior Structurer/Structuring Analyst (quantitative finance degree required)
- Progression: Structurer (3-6 yrs) → Senior Structurer (6-10 yrs) → Head of Structuring (10+ yrs) → MD/Global Head, or lateral moves to derivatives trading, quantitative research, buy-side portfolio management, corporate treasury, fintech leadership

